## Overview
**Muhammad Ali** (born **Cassius Marcellus Clay Jr.**, January 17, 1942 – June 3, 2016) was an American professional boxer, activist, and philanthropist. Widely regarded as one of the greatest athletes of all time, Ali transcended sports to become a global icon, known for his athletic prowess, outspoken personality, and commitment to social justice.

---

## Key Details

- **Born:** January 17, 1942, in Louisville, Kentucky  
- **Died:** June 3, 2016, in Scottsdale, Arizona  
- **Occupation:** Boxer, Activist, Philanthropist  
- **Known For:**  
  - Winning the **1960 Rome Olympics** gold medal in light heavyweight boxing  
  - Being a three-time lineal heavyweight champion  
  - Advocacy for civil rights and opposition to the Vietnam War  

---

## Timeline

- **1960 (20th Century):** Won gold at the Rome Olympics.  
- **1964 (20th Century):** Defeated Sonny Liston to become world heavyweight champion; converted to Islam and changed name to Muhammad Ali.  
- **1967 (20th Century):** Refused military draft for the Vietnam War; stripped of his title and banned from boxing.  
- **1971 (20th Century):** Supreme Court overturned his draft evasion conviction; lost "Fight of the Century" to Joe Frazier.  
- **1974 (20th Century):** Defeated George Foreman in the "Rumble in the Jungle" to reclaim heavyweight title.  
- **1975 (20th Century):** Won "Thrilla in Manila" against Joe Frazier.  
- **1984 (20th Century):** Diagnosed with Parkinson's disease.  
- **2005 (21st Century):** Awarded the Presidential Medal of Freedom.  
- **2016 (21st Century):** Passed away from septic shock.  

